  <hr />
  <p>
    A mascot is not a character. It is a failure signature — the specific category
    of wrongness a system embodied in public, given a face so the archive could
    cross-reference it. If you see the same <code>mascotRef</code> across multiple
    case files, the same kind of problem is asking for your attention.
  </p>
  <p>
    The <a href="/mascots">Mascot Registry</a> lists all known entries sorted by ID.
    This page is the interpretive layer: how mascots are used, what they are
    allowed to mean, and which incident clusters called specific ones into existence.
  </p>

  <h2>Behavioral Rules</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Mascots are failure signatures. They must remain attached to specific kinds of wrongness.</li>
    <li>No new mascot without at least one Lorelog case proving which failure it belongs to.</li>
    <li>A mascot may change aesthetics. It may not change its failure domain without filing an identity drift incident.</li>
    <li>If UI copy treats a mascot as a cheerleader rather than a witness, the archive may repossess it.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Key Incident Anchors</h2>
